</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uscarsoulklaw.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ScarSoulKlaw</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are Superior</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#FF0000>(6/20/02 9:13:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthebattlefield.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=950.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: what makes a good warrior?</span><hr size=1> This is a great thread.  One thing I would like to add is flexibility - in 2 forms.<br>
<br>
The first is leadership/guidance.  Be willing to try things, work with your group and discuss options.  Wins are sweeter and losses don't hurt as bad when everyone has a hand in it.<br>
<br>
The other is in your equipment choices.  A group has people go LD or leave suddenly that you were counting on to perform a key function.  Now what do you do?  You grab the item from your bag that helps replace the skills you just lost and encourage the group to understand that with a little assistance you'll all be just fine.<br>
<br>
There are a wide variety of items and techniques a warrior can use to emulate other classes specialty skills - snare, heal, DoT, slow, fear (blinding), stun.  Don't hesitate to keep a few with you.  I carry no less than 7 weapons on me at all times.  As such I can step in for a number of different functions if someone is LOM or OOM and do my best to keep it all together.  Slow, heal, DoT/Snare, Stun and extra bandages are all a proc away.  Sure it's a gamble sometimes but that's what makes the game exciting.  The adventure and teasing lady Luck at the same time as you're taunting the mobs.<br>
<br>
Using these will help to build your knowledge of the other classes and how they view situations.  I have learned a lot from getting tactical ideas from various sources and fitting the pieces together.  It doesn't always work but we almost always come out laughing.  It has also built other players trust in me and my abilites.<br>
<br>
Key points - talk, ask questions if you're not sure about how certain classes work, and try to keep a few surprises in your bag. <p>Scartle SoulKlaw<br>
Dwarven Myrmidon of The Amber Order</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uzytalius71.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zytalius71</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are Superior</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#FF0000>(6/20/02 9:21:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthebattlefield.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=950.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: If you don't mind me answering ;)</span><hr size=1> Yeah cant think of anything else to say that hasnt been said already.  People nailed it on the head, just read all the previous posts.  <br>
<br>
To tell a little story though which kinda applies to the original post.<br>
<br>
Back in the day when I played (No Flames Please) A Paladin, I was in the long forgotten Cazic Thule (Great zone).  Along came this Barb Warrior name Draviin (I still remember his name after 2 years).  He had some pretty decent gear for his level, but that isnt why I remember him.  <br>
<br>
He took charged of the group.  Not bossy, but he let you know what was going on.  How it should go, and corrected you if you were wrong.  But did it nicely or with humor.  He knew exactly where to pull, when to pull, what to pull, and how many to pull.  Knew when to stop for breaks, mana, nature calls, etc...  Even when things got outta control with agro's or trains, he handled it perfectly.  No one ever died on his watch.  Though he leveled faster than me, the 3 or 4 times I grouped with him has stuck with me until now.  <br>
<br>
